statement:
In the following figure, the curved graph is a demand curve where
\emph{q} is the demand and \emph{p} is the price in dollars. The
straight line is the tangent line to this demand curve at the point
\emph{(p,q) = (2,6)}. Recall that the price elasticity of demand is
given by

\begin{align*}\epsilon(p) = \frac{p}{q} \frac{dq}{dp}\end{align*}

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{Math_Exam_Resources_Courses_MATH104_December2011_Question_5_(a).jpg}
\end{description}

\textbf{(a)} Comput $\epsilon(2)$, the elasticity at price \$2.
